	<annotations>
		<text id="0" type="text/plain" rect="(637.0, 159.0, 409.0, 69.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Data is too big, so need to use Data Sampler to split the data into smaller sections and then save the data.
</text>
		<text id="1" type="text/plain" rect="(460.0273874732079, 684.0546955624354, 390.0, 88.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Shows how many transactions are fraud or legit</text>
		<text id="2" type="text/plain" rect="(463.7543859649122, 769.0175438596493, 342.0, 50.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Shows how much money was spent on fraud or legit transactions</text>
		<text id="3" type="text/plain" rect="(478.0068352699931, 471.0207336523124, 329.0, 72.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Shows 5% of the data as data has been split because of the size</text>
		<text id="4" type="text/plain" rect="(68.01595331007093, 1294.6204034439327, 162.16216216216216, 72.97297297297303)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Set Class as target</text>
		<text id="5" type="text/plain" rect="(46.7056965042251, 1216.0870439297746, 232.43243243243242, 70.2702702702702)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Type: Classification </text>
		<text id="6" type="text/plain" rect="(220.03225532637293, 1286.104744928274, 125.39682539682536, 50.79365079365073)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Takes Top 10 Features</text>
		<text id="7" type="text/plain" rect="(339.07987437399197, 1290.8666496901785, 152.38095238095235, 50.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Normalizes to [0, 1]</text>
		<text id="8" type="text/plain" rect="(947.4137590068487, 1243.314860612966, 124.57627118644075, 50.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Predicts the data </text>
		<text id="9" type="text/plain" rect="(935.7438506989854, 1514.501301290932, 118.64406779661022, 69.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Trains the data and reports score</text>
		<text id="10" type="text/plain" rect="(1096.760799851528, 1588.230114850254, 118.64406779661022, 69.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">2x2 true/fasle positives and negatives</text>
		<text id="11" type="text/plain" rect="(1105.1819328489323, 1252.0337489928716, 115.25423728813553, 107.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Distinguishes fraud transactions from legit transactions</text>
		<text id="12" type="text/plain" rect="(614.5574100210195, 1159.2131656977115, 156.77966101694915, 50.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Separates "fraud" from "not fraud"</text>
		<text id="13" type="text/plain" rect="(626.2014778176292, 1416.9758775621183, 107.62711864406776, 69.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Asks yes/no questions and votes</text>
		<text id="14" type="text/plain" rect="(621.3370710379684, 1580.6029962061864, 113.55932203389841, 107.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Looks at past results and whatever is more is the prediction </text>
		<text id="15" type="text/plain" rect="(798.6094880080447, 1739.912812135133, 377.9661016949152, 335.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">kNN is the best model because of its score of F1, Recall, and MCC. It catches more real fraud transactions compared to the other 2 models. It matters because for a banks, missing real fraud (False Negative) is much more costly than occasionally flagging a legitimate transaction (False Positive). A model that catches more fraud, even with few more False Positive is safer and valuable than ones that don't.


</text>
		<text id="16" type="text/plain" rect="(622.2160620937032, 1998.2287591749064, 350.0000000000001, 696.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">

F1:

- balances Precision and Recall together
- one number that punishes a model for being unbalanced


Precision:

- when the model predicts fruad, how often is it correct



Recall:

- out of all the actual fraud cases, what % did the model successfully catch




MCC (Mathews Correlation Coefficient):

- overall quality of the model
- considers 4 outcomes at once (Confusion Matrix):
        1. correctly caught fraud
        2. correctly cleared legitimate
        3. missed fraud
        4. false alarms

- produces one number from -1 ( always wrong to 0 (random guessing) to 1 (perfect)</text>
		<text id="17" type="text/plain" rect="(1304.8720103398323, 1757.2605225091322, 221.64948453608235, 304.1237113402062)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Model:


Logistic Regression



Random Forest



kNN

</text>
		<text id="18" type="text/plain" rect="(1516.2431443604505, 1751.914198729819, 202.0618556701031, 292.7835051546392)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">F1


0.438



0.667



0.714</text>
		<text id="19" type="text/plain" rect="(1652.7276804429252, 1748.7904873896123, 245.36082474226805, 304.1237113402062)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">Recall

0.292




0.583




0.625</text>
		<text id="20" type="text/plain" rect="(1779.6757103821992, 1747.6561843250756, 159.79381443298985, 278.0)" font-family=".AppleSystemUIFont" font-size="16">MCC

0.505




0.673




0.721
</text>
